In Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete the variables no_qual_M_25_64, no_qual_F_25_64 and no_qual_T_25_64 give the number of men, women and total population aged 25-64 with no educational qualifications. Calculate the percent of men, women and total population in that age range with no qualifications. Use the variables all_M_25_64, all_F_25_64 and all_T_25_64 as denominators. How many datazones (spatial administrative unit in Scotland) have over 20% of people aged 25-64 with no qualifications?
Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$percentage_M <- (Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$no_qual_M_25_64 / Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$all_M_25_64) * 100
Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$percentage_F <- (Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$no_qual_F_25_64 / Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$all_F_25_64) * 100
Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$percentage_T <- (Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$no_qual_T_25_64 / Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$all_T_25_64) * 100
print(paste("Percentage of males without qualifications: ", mean(Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$percentage_M, na.rm = TRUE), "%"))

  1. Summarize the variable UR8FOLD. What type is this variable? Create an ordered factor variable of the 8-fold urban-rural classification. The description of the categories is in the file SGUR2011_2012_UR8FOLD_CodeDesc.txt. Try to use short but descriptive variable labels. To learn more about UR8FOLD (2016 Urban Rural Classification. Classification identifying urban and rural areas based on settlement size and drive times) go to https://www.gov.scot/publications/scottish-government-urban-rural-classification-2016/pages/6/ .

UR8FOLD is a level 8-fold urban-rural classification variable.

  1. Create a three category variable from the 8-fold urban-rural classification that groups datazones into accessible areas (including urban areas), remote areas and very remote areas.
Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$UR8FOLD <- as.numeric(Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$UR8FOLD)

Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete <- Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete %>% mutate(UR3FOLD = case_when(Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$UR8FOLD %in% c(1, 2, 3, 6) ~ "accessible areas ", Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$UR8FOLD %in% c(4, 7) ~ "remote areas", Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$UR8FOLD %in% c(5, 8) ~ "very remote areas"))

Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$UR3FOLD <- factor(Deprivation_Scotland_2011DZ_complete$UR3FOLD, levels = c("accessible areas ", "remote areas", "very remote areas"))

1. Make a population density map of the world.

  • use library library(sf) to load COUNTRIES_ALL shapefile as Countries (you can name this dataset as you wish).

  • some of the rows in the dataset have NA values - in order to delete them make a subset of Countries with rows where Pop2015 is higher than 0 (or eliminate rows with NA values).

  • you do not have a variable Population density 2015 in the COuntries or Countries2 datasets. You need to create it by adding a new variable POP_DENS. Population density equals a total number of people divided by squared area POP2015/SQKM.

  • create a choropleth map showing population density in the countries of the world.

  • use 7 classes to visualise your population density into classes.

other dividing method: fisher, jenks(Jenks natural breaks), kmeans, pretty, equal(Equal interval), sd(Standard deviation), histogram, quantile.

  • look at the classInt or tmap tm_scale_intervals documentation in order to identify the best classification method. The best will be the one which shows your pattern in the clearest way.

  • you can use RColorBrewer library in order to identify the scheme of colours of your choice or tmap brewer choices.

Countries <- st_read("~/Downloads/lab 1_ 2025/Data_assignment/COUNTRIES_ALL.shp")
## Reading layer `COUNTRIES_ALL' from data source 
##   `/Users/llllllyh/Downloads/lab 1_ 2025/Data_assignment/COUNTRIES_ALL.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 247 features and 7 fields
## Geometry type: MULTIPOLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -180 ymin: -58.49861 xmax: 180 ymax: 83.6236
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
Countries2 <- subset(Countries, Countries$POP2015 > 0)
Countries2$POP_DENS <- Countries2$POP2015 / Countries2$SQKM
Countries2 <- Countries2[!is.na(Countries2$POP_DENS) & Countries2$POP_DENS > 0, ]
breaks <- classIntervals(Countries2$POP_DENS, n = 7, style = "quantile")$brks

tm_shape(Countries2) + tm_polygons("POP_DENS", palette = "YlOrRd", breaks = breaks, title = "Population Density (per sq.km)") + tm_layout(main.title = "World Population Density - 2015", legend.outside = TRUE)

2. Make a map of China with Chinese big cities

  • make a subset of dataset Countries where you choose only one county - China

  • use library library(sf) to load cities file. You can name it cities

  • in order to choose only Chinese cities you can use raster library and intersect command. You can also use st_intersecting as we did in the tutorials.

  • Name the new dataset Chinese_cities

  • plot a map of China with a background colour of your choice

  • plot Chinese cities on the top map of China.You can decide what colour and size the symbols will be. Make sure they are visible on your final map.

  • add labels to the cities. Use CITY_NAME variable for this purpose.

  • add legend and a title to your map

Countries <- st_read("~/Downloads/lab 1_ 2025/Data_assignment/COUNTRIES_ALL.shp")
## Reading layer `COUNTRIES_ALL' from data source 
##   `/Users/llllllyh/Downloads/lab 1_ 2025/Data_assignment/COUNTRIES_ALL.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 247 features and 7 fields
## Geometry type: MULTIPOLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -180 ymin: -58.49861 xmax: 180 ymax: 83.6236
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
China<-subset(Countries,Countries$CNTRY_NAME=="China")

cities <- st_read("~/Downloads/lab 1_ 2025/Data_assignment/cities.shp")
## Reading layer `cities' from data source 
##   `/Users/llllllyh/Downloads/lab 1_ 2025/Data_assignment/cities.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 48 features and 8 fields
## Geometry type: POINT
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -118.25 ymin: -33.47502 xmax: 139.809 ymax: 59.91666
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
Chinese_cities <- cities[st_intersects(cities, China, sparse = FALSE), ]

plot(st_geometry(China), col = "grey", main = "Map of China with Major Cities", axes = TRUE)
plot(st_geometry(Chinese_cities), add = TRUE, col = "red", pch = 19, cex = 0.5)
text(st_coordinates(Chinese_cities), labels = Chinese_cities$CITY_NAME, cex = 0.6, pos = 4, col = "black")
legend("topright", legend = "Major Cities", pch = 19, cex = 1, col = "red")

3. Make a map using tmap library

  • make a map of population density of the world with plotted proportional symbols of the worlds cities population from 2015.

  • to make this map you can follow the example from the lab

  • choose quantile classification and create 6 classes for POP

  • using tm_bubbles create proportional symbols from a variable POPULATION from your cities dataset

  • add title and legends for both datasets

  • make sure your code, comments and the resulting maps are visible in the document.

Countries2 <- subset(Countries, Countries$POP2015 > 0 & Countries$SQKM > 0)
Countries2$POP_DENS <- Countries2$POP2015 / Countries2$SQKM
Countries2 <- Countries2[!is.na(Countries2$POP_DENS) & is.finite(Countries2$POP_DENS), ]
Cities2 <- subset(cities, cities$POPULATION > 0)
breaks <- classIntervals(Countries2$POP_DENS, n = 6, style = "quantile")$brks

Countries2$POP_DENS <- as.numeric(Countries2$POP_DENS)
tm_shape(Countries2) + tm_polygons("POP_DENS", title = "Population Density", palette = "YlOrRd", style = "quantile", n = 6) + tm_shape(Cities2) + tm_bubbles(size = "POPULATION", col = "blue", alpha = 0.5, title.size = "City Population") + tm_layout(title = "World Population Density and City Populations", legend.outside = TRUE)
